---
import ArticleLayout from '../layouts/ArticleLayout.astro';
import Reassurance from '../components/Reassurance.astro';
import MidCta from '../components/MidCta.astro';
import PullQuote from '../components/PullQuote.astro';
import FaqSection from '../components/FaqSection.astro';
import CtaBlock from '../components/CtaBlock.astro';
import EnquiryForm from '../components/locked/EnquiryForm.astro';
import RelatedPanel from '../components/RelatedPanel.astro';

const slug = '/merchant-navy-mortgage';

const reassuranceLines = [
  'Pay that combines sterling and a foreign currency.',
  'Rotational contracts with long spells at sea.',
  'Income covered by the Seafarers Earnings Deduction.',
  'Limited recent UK address history.',
];

const faqs = [
  {
    q: 'Can a merchant navy seafarer get a UK mortgage?',
    a: 'Yes. Merchant navy pay is placed across multiple lenders in the market every week. The work is in matching how you are paid to a lender that assesses seafarers by hand rather than by an automated check.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Does foreign currency pay reduce what I can borrow?',
    a: 'It can. A lender converts non-sterling pay to sterling and applies a reduction for exchange rate movement. The size of that reduction varies between lenders, so the lender you choose affects your borrowing more than the rate does.',
  },
  {
    q: 'What evidence should I have ready?',
    a: 'Your current contract, recent payslips, bank statements showing the pay arriving, and your discharge book to evidence sea time. If you claim the Seafarers Earnings Deduction, records that support the claim help too.',
  },
  {
    q: 'How do I start?',
    a: 'Use the 60-second check and a Mortgage One adviser will review your answers and tell you where you stand. You can also call us on 01202 155992. You must be on UK soil to receive advice.',
  },
];

const relatedCards = [
  { title: 'Mortgages for seafarers', href: '/mortgage-as-a-seafarer', line: 'The full picture for seafarer mortgages.' },
  { title: 'Foreign currency income', href: '/seafarer-mortgage-foreign-currency-income', line: 'How lenders convert and discount non-sterling pay.' },
  { title: 'Seafarers Earnings Deduction mortgages', href: '/seafarers-earnings-deduction-mortgage', line: 'Getting a mortgage while you claim the Seafarers Earnings Deduction.' },
  { title: 'Check your eligibility', href: '/check', line: 'Five quick questions, about 60 seconds.' },
];
---

<ArticleLayout
  title="Merchant Navy Mortgages: Specialist Help | Mortgage One"
  description="Yes, merchant navy seafarers can get a UK mortgage. How the right lender handles rotational contracts, foreign currency pay and time at sea by hand."
  eyebrow="Seafarer mortgage questions"
  heading="Can a merchant navy seafarer get a UK mortgage?"
  breadcrumbs={[
    { name: 'Home', href: '/' },
    { name: 'Can a merchant navy seafarer get a UK mortgage?', href: slug },
  ]}
  scenario="seafarer"
>
  <p>
    Yes. Merchant navy seafarers get UK mortgages across multiple lenders in the market. Merchant navy pay can combine
    several things a high street system struggles with at once, foreign currency, rotational contracts, long spells at
    sea and the Seafarers' Earnings Deduction (SED). None of that is unusual to a lender that knows seafarers. The case
    is assessed by hand, by someone who has seen it before, rather than by a tick box.
  </p>

  <Reassurance title="Situations we see regularly" lines={reassuranceLines} />

  <h2>Why is a merchant navy mortgage treated as specialist?</h2>
  <p>
    On their own, each part of merchant navy pay is manageable. Together, they confuse an automated check. Foreign
    currency, a rotational pattern, months away and a low tax bill from SED can each trip a high street system, even
    when the underlying income is strong. A lender used to seafarers reads these features as normal, because for this
    line of work they are.
  </p>

  <h2>Does foreign currency pay reduce what I can borrow?</h2>
  <p>
    Often part of merchant navy pay arrives in US dollars or euros. A lender converts it to sterling and applies a
    reduction to allow for the rate moving, then lends on a percentage of that figure. Because the size of the reduction
    varies, the lender you choose matters. We explain this in detail on our
    <a href="/seafarer-mortgage-foreign-currency-income">foreign currency income</a> page.
  </p>

  <MidCta
    text="Tell us how your pay is made up and we will tell you where you stand."
    scenario="seafarer"
    src={slug}
  />

  <h2>What about the Seafarers' Earnings Deduction?</h2>
  <p>
    Many merchant navy seafarers claim SED, which removes UK income tax on qualifying earnings worked outside the UK.
    That can make your taxable income look low to an automated check, even though your contracted pay is steady. The
    right lender assesses your gross contractual earnings instead. There is more on this on our
    <a href="/seafarers-earnings-deduction-mortgage">Seafarers Earnings Deduction</a> page.
  </p>

  <PullQuote quote="Merchant navy pay only looks complicated to a lender that does not know seafarers. The right one assesses it by hand." />

  <h2>How do rotational contracts and time at sea look to a lender?</h2>
  <p>
    Rotational contracts, fixed periods on and off, and long stretches at sea are routine for merchant navy crew. A
    lender that understands the sector treats a settled rotation as stable employment rather than a gap. What it wants
    to see is a clear, regular pattern of pay that is likely to continue.
  </p>

  <h2>What evidence will a lender want?</h2>
  <p>
    Have your current contract, recent payslips and bank statements showing the pay arriving, and your discharge book to
    evidence sea time. If you claim SED, keep records that support the claim, such as your tax return and days worked
    outside the UK. Clear paperwork lets an underwriter see the whole picture quickly.
  </p>

  <h2>How does residency affect the lender list and deposit?</h2>
  <p>
    Your tax residency and recent UK address history shape which lenders will help and how much deposit they ask for.
    UK-resident merchant navy seafarers can often reach standard deposit levels, subject to criteria, while non-resident
    cases tend to need a larger deposit. You must be on UK soil to receive advice, so we confirm your circumstances
    before recommending anything.
  </p>

  <MidCta
    text="Merchant navy pay made up of several parts? Let us put it in front of the right lender."
    label="Check Your Options"
    scenario="seafarer"
    src={slug}
  />

  <FaqSection items={faqs} />

  <CtaBlock
    heading="Find out where you stand"
    line="Tell us how your pay is made up and a Mortgage One adviser will review your answers."
    scenario="seafarer"
    src={slug}
  />

  <EnquiryForm scenario="seafarer" />

  <RelatedPanel cards={relatedCards} />

  <p class="risk-warning">
    Think carefully before securing your debts against your home. Your home may be repossessed if you do not keep up
    repayments on your mortgage.
  </p>
</ArticleLayout>

<style>
  .risk-warning {
    border-top: 1px solid var(--line);
    padding-top: 1.5rem;
    margin-top: 2.5rem;
  }
</style>
